alian:","from the feminine form of   Zello  .","alternatively, perhaps a variant of   Cella  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Zello","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Rocco.","Italian:","from a short form of a medieval personal name ending with the hypocoristic suffix <i>-zello</i>, such as for example <i>Donzello</i>."]}]},{"name":"Scala","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Luigi, Sal, Antonio, Carmine, Corrado, Orazio, Tiziana, Aldo, Angelo, Carlo, Carmela, Concetta.","Italian: topographic name from <i>scala</i> ‘ladder, flight of steps; wharf’ for someone who lived by a flight of steps or on terraced land; or a habitational name from any of various places called with this word, as for example Scala in Salerno province, Scala Coeli in Cosenza, or the district so named in Torregrotta, in Messina province, Sicily. Compare   Di Scala   and   La Scala  .","Americanized form of Czech <b>Skála</b>, Polish and Jewish (from Poland) <b>Skała</b>, or Slovak and Rusyn   Skala  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Di Scala","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Emidio, Luigi, Nicola, Paolo.","Italian: habitational name for someone from any of various places places named with <i>scala</i> ‘ladder, flight of steps; wharf’ (see   Scala  )."]},{"name":"Scalese","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Salvatore, Angelo, Gennaro, Guido, Pasquale, Vincenzo.","Italian (southern): probably a habitational name for someone from Scala in Salerno province (see   Scala  )."]},{"name":"Scalera","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Domenic, Vito, Angelo, Carmine, Ciro, Gilda, Lorenzo, Luciano, Pasquale.","Italian:","habitational name from a district so named in Filiano in Potenza province."]},{"name":"La Scala","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Salvatore, Faust, Natale, Nicola, Silvio.","Italian (also <b>Lascala</b>): variant of   Scala  , with the addition of the definite article <i>la</i>."]},{"name":"Skala","meanings":["Czech (<b>Skála</b>); Slovak (also <b>Skála</b>); Polish and Jewish (from Poland) (<b>Skała</b>); Rusyn (from Slovakia and Poland; in Poland spelled <b>Skała</b>): topographic name for someone who lived by a rock or crag, Czech <i>skála</i>, Slovak and Rusyn <i>skala</i>, Polish <i>skała</i>. As a Jewish surname this is often artificial. Compare   Scala   and   Skalla  ."]},{"name":"Scali","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Salvatore, Domenic, Antonio, Geraldo, Orlando, Pasquale, Rocco, Carmela, Cesare, Fortunato, Giuseppe, Mauro, Pasqualina, Piero, Rosario, Saverio.","Italian (southern):","habitational name from Scali in Piedimonte Etneo, Sicily, named with Greek <i>skali(n)</i> ‘step, terrace’ (itself derived from Latin <i>scala</i> ‘ladder’), or from some other similarly named place."]}]},{"name":"Jacopino","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Italian: variant of   Iacovino  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Iacovino","meanings":["Italian: from the personal name <i>Iacovino</i>, a pet form of <i>Iacovo</i> from Latin <i>Iacobus</i> (see   Jacob  )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Jacopino Della Scala was born in 1210, in Verona, Veneto, Italy as the son of Leonardino Sigiberto della Scala Duque de Mantua. He married Margarete Guistiniani. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in his hometown."},"et":{"1210–":"1210–Surnud","1210–Male":"1210–Surnud","1189–Female":"1189–Surnud","1195–Female":"1195–Surnud","1214–Male":"1214–Surnud","1260–1277":"1260–1277","–1301":"–1301","–Male":"Surnud","1230–Female":"1230–Surnud","1214":"1214","1301":"1301","1277":"1277","1189":"1189","1210":"1210","about 1214":"umbes 1214","1230":"1230","1195":"1195","1260":"1260","Verona, Veneto, Italia":"Verona, Veneto, Itaalia","Verona, Venezien, Italien":"Verona, Veneto, Itaalia","Italy":"Itaalia","Ve